Selective breeding can result in hybrids. A hybrid results when two separate species mate to produce offspring. For example, when a lion mates with a tiger, they produce a liger. Or, when a donkey mates with a horse, they produce a mule!

Hybrids can be the result of humans selectively breeding different species to mate, or they can be the result of different species making this decision on their own in the wild. Oftentimes hybrids are sterile, meaning they cannot reproduce and make offspring. This is because of the difference in chromosome numbers between both parents. Yet, sometimes, hybrids can reproduce and they go on to create their own unique species.

Read this article to explore more examples of how hybrids show up in both nature and in human-controlled breeding.

Use this strategy to help you interpret your graph to state evidence-based claims. The Identify and Interpret Strategy involves the following steps:
  • First, look at your graph and identify any patterns or trends that stand out to you by writing "What I see" comments.
  • Then, interpret the meaning of each "What I see" comment by writing a "What it means" comment.
  • Lastly, write a complete caption below your graph using your stated comments.

If interested in the alternative Final Product of a Scientific Journal Article, refer to this resource to see an example of what you can turn in for this project. This example shows the published results of a Body Response Investigation carried out by students who were interested in the question: "What emotional and physical effects does different types of music have on people?" Note how the students structured their journal article and the formal language used to write their article.

The Cognitive Skills Book of Truth is the core handbook for all inquiries related to the Cognitive Skills. Use the book to learn more about each Cognitive Skills' standards alignment, related instructional strategies, disciplinary relevance, and to dig into differences in student performance across score levels.

The Summit Learning Cognitive Skills Rubric is an assessment and instruction tool that outlines the continuum of skills that are necessary for college and career readiness. Cognitive Skills are interdisciplinary skills that require higher-order thinking and application, such as Making Connections and Inferences and Evaluating Arguments.

 

All Cognitive Skill resources can also be accessed in this Cognitive Skills folder.
